<section>
<title>Compactness</title>

<definition>
  <statement>
    <p>A set <m>K \subset \mathbb{R}</m> is <term>(sequentially) compact</term> if every sequences in <m>K</m> has a subsequence that converges in <m>K</m>.</p>
  </statement>
</definition>

<theorem>
    <statement>
      <p>A set<m>K \subset \mathbb{R}</m> is (sequentially) compact if and only if <m>K</m> is closed and bounded.</p>
    </statement>
  </theorem>

<theorem>
  <title>Heine-Borel</title>
  <statement>
    <p>A set <m>K \subset \mathbb{R}</m> is compact if and only if every open cover of <m>K</m> contains a finite subcover.</p>
  </statement>
</theorem>

<p>
  Note writing ``<m>K</m> has the Heine-Borel property'' means that ``every open cover of <m>K</m> has a finite subcover.'' 
</p>

<proof>
  <p>
   (<m>\Leftarrow</m>) Suppose <m>K</m> has the property that every open cover of <m>K</m> has a finite subcover.  This is called the Heine-Borel property.  We want to show that <m>K</m> is sequentially compact.  We will do this by showing that <m>K</m> is closed and bounded.
  </p>
  <p>
    To show that <m>K</m> is bounded, consider the open sets
    <md>
      <mrow> V_1(x)\amp =\{y \in \mathbb{R}\, : \, |x-y| &lt; 1\} </mrow>.
    </md>
    These are the <m>1-</m>neighborhoods of <m>x</m>.  Then the collection <m>\{v_1(x)\}_{x \in K}</m> is an open cover of <m>K</m>.  Since <m>K</m> has the Heine-Borel property, this open cover has a finite subcover <m>\{V_1(x_k)\}_{k=1}^n</m>, noting that <m>x_k \in K</m> for all <m>k</m>.
  </p>
    </proof>

    </section>
  
<!-- ========================================   -->

<section>

  <proof>
  <p>
    Without loss of generality, we can assume that <m>x_i &lt; x_{i+1}</m> for <m>1=1,2,3,\ldots,N-1</m>.  Then
    <md>
      <mrow> x_1 -1 \amp &lt; x &lt; x_n+1 </mrow>
    </md>
    so <m>K</m> is bounded by <m>\max\{|x_1-1|,x_{n}+1|\}</m>.
  </p>
  <p>
    To show that <m>K</m> is closed we argue indirectly.  Suppose <m>(y_k) \subset K</m> is a Cauchy sequence with limit <m>y</m>.  This means that <m>y</m> is a limit point of <m>K</m>.  We need to show <m>y \in K</m>.
  </p>
  <p workspace="2in">
    Suppose not.  Suppose <m>y \notin K</m>.  Then <m>|x-y| &gt; 0</m> for all <m>x \in K</m>.  (The inequality equals zero precisely when <m>x=y</m>.). Define
    <md>
      <mrow>\mathcal{O}_x \amp =\{u \in K \, : \, |u-x| &lt; \frac{1}{2}|x-y|\}</mrow>
    </md>
  </p>
  <p>The closer <m>x</m> is to <m>y</m>, the smaller the radius of <m>\mathcal{O}_x</m>.  The collection <m>\{\mathcal{O}_x\}_{x \in K}</m> is an open cover of <m>K</m>.  By the Heine-Borel property, this open cover has a finite subcover, <m>\{\mathcal{O}_{x_i}\}_{i=1}^{n}</m>.
  </p>
  <p>
    Consider <m>\epsilon_0 = \min\{\frac{1}{2}|x_i-y|\}</m>, which is the smallest radius of the open sets in our finite subcover.  Since <m>(y_n) \rightarrow y</m>, there is an <m>N &gt; 0</m> such that <m>|y_n-y| &lt; \epsilon_0</m> for <m>n &gt; N</m>.  But these <m>y_n</m> are outside every <m>\mathcal{O}_{x_i}</m>.  So out purported finite subcover does not cover <m>K</m>!  This is a contradicion.
  </p>
  <p>
    Consequently, <m>K</m> is compact.
  </p>
  </proof>


</section>

<section>
  <title>The Heine-Borel Property</title>
  
  <example>
    <title>The singleton set has the Heine-Borel property</title>
        
  <p>
    Let <m>x \in \mathbb{R}</m> and consider <m>F=\{x\}</m>, the singleton set.
  </p>
  <p>
    What would an open cover of <m>F</m> look like.  Consider <m>I=(a,b)</m> where <m>a &lt; x &lt; b</m>.  Then <m>x \in I</m>.  The collection <m>\mathcal{U}=\{I\}</m> is an open cover of <m>F</m>.
  </p>
  <p>
    Suppose <m>\mathcal{U}=\{U_{\lambda}\,:\, \lambda \in \Lambda \}</m> is an open cover of <m>F</m>.   This means
    <md>
      <mrow>F \amp \subset \bigcup_{\lambda \in \Lambda} U_{\lambda}.</mrow>
    </md>
    So <m>x \in U_{\lambda_0}</m> for some <m>\lambda_0 \in \Lambda</m>.  Let's define <m>\mathcal{U}_0 = \{ U_{\lambda_0}\}</m>.  Then <m>\mathcal{U}_0 \subset \mathcal{U}</m> is a subset of our open cover of <m>F</m>.  And because <m>\mathcal{U}_0</m> is a finite collection, it is a finite subcover of <m>\mathcal{U}</m>.
  </p>
  <p>
    Note that we've just proved that <m>F=\{x\}</m> has the Heine-Borel property.  That is to say, <m>\{x\}</m> is a compact set.
  </p>  
  </example>
  
  <example>
    <title>A finite set has the Heine-Borel property</title>
        
  <p>
    Let <m>x_i \in \mathbb{R}</m> and consider <m>F=\{x_1,x_2,x_3,\ldots,x_n\}</m>.  Suppose <m>\mathcal{U}=\{U_{\lambda}\,:\, \lambda \in \Lambda \}</m> is an open cover of <m>F</m>.   This means
    <md>
      <mrow>F \amp \subset \bigcup_{\lambda \in \Lambda} U_{\lambda}.</mrow>
    </md>
    Let's see how to extract a finite subcover of <m>F</m> from <m>\mathcal{U}</m>.  Take <m>x_1 \in F</m>.  Since <m>\mathcal{U}</m> is an open cover of <m>F</m>, <m>x_1 \in \bigcup_{\lambda \in \Lambda} U_{\lambda}</m>.  This means <m>x_1 \in U_{\lambda_1}</m> for some <m>\lambda_1 \in \Lambda</m>.  Set this open set aside for our finite subcover, then consider <m>x_2 \in \bigcup_{\lambda \in \Lambda} U_{\lambda}</m>.  This means <m>x_2 \in U_{\lambda_2}</m> for some <m>\lambda_2 \in \Lambda</m>.  Add this set to our collection of open set, then repeat this process for each <m>x_k</m> that remains to find <m>U_{\lambda_k}</m> containing <m>x_k</m>.  When we exhaust the numbers in <m>F</m>, we end up with a collection of at most <m>n</m> open sets <m>\{ U_{\lambda_k} \, : \, 1 \leq k \leq n\}</m>.  This is a finite subcover of <m>F</m>.
  </p>
  <p>
    This proves that <m>F</m> has the Heine-Borel property.  That is to say, <m>\{x_1, x_2, x_3, \ldots, x_n\}</m> is a compact set.
  </p>
  </example>

<example>
    <title>The open interval <m>(0,1)</m> does not have the Heine-Borel property</title>
        
  <p>
    Let <m>\mathcal{O}=(0,1)</m>.  Let 
    <md>
      <mrow>
        \mathcal{U} \amp =\{ (\epsilon,1) \subset \mathbb{R} \, : \, 0 &lt; \epsilon &lt; 1\}
      </mrow>
    </md>
  This is an open cover of <m>\mathcal{O}</m> because given any <m>x \in \mathcal{O}</m>, there is an <m>\epsilon &gt; 0</m> with <m>0 &lt; \epsilon &lt; x</m>.  Thus <m>x \in (\epsilon,1)</m>, an open set in the collection <m>\mathcal{U}</m>.  
  </p>
  <p>
    If <m>\mathcal{O}</m> had the Heine-Borel property, <m>\mathcal{U}</m> would have a finite subcover, <m>\mathcal{U}_0</m>.  But then the intervals in the subcover would have a smallest left endpoint, <m>\epsilon_0 &gt; 0</m>.  By the Archimedean Property of the reals, this leaves real numbers between 0 and <m>\epsilon_0</m> uncovered!  Thus <m>\mathcal{U}_0</m> could not be a cover of <m>(0,1)</m>.
  </p>
  <p>
    This shows that <m>\mathcal{O}</m> does not have the Heine-Borel property.  That is to say, <m>\mathcal{O}</m> is not compact.
  </p>
  </example>

</section>

<!-- ============================ -->

<section>
  <title>Heine-Borel Theorem</title>
  
<theorem xml:id="thm-heine-borel">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Let <m>K \subset \mathbb{R}</m>.  All of the following statements are equivalent in the sense that any one implies all of the others.
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>K</m> is compact.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>K</m> is closed and bounded.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Every open cover of <m>K</m> has a finite subcover.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </statement>
</theorem>

<p>
  Compact sets will play an important role as we develop the theory of functions, next.
</p>

</section>

